Pisgah Penny is a white Tree Squirrel who makes an annual prediction for “White Squirrel Day” in Brevard, North Carolina. White Squirrel Day is similar in many respects to Groundhog Day, the primary difference being the substitution of a groudhog for a squirrel. Penny’s predictions are based on what side of her display cage she moves to, one side signifying early spring and the other six more weeks winter. Brevard Mayor Maureen Copelof says “Pisgah Penny has established herself as a beloved and valued member of this community who openly asserts her love for Brevard,” while “Punxsutawney Phil has established himself as, let’s be honest, an ill tempered, unreliable predictor.”

$lotsinlife A lot starts small, but a lot never stays one lot for long, not a lot of time. One lot leads to another lot, and another lot after that, a lot alotted until the whole lot becomes a lot of lots. Every lot is allotted a place—one lot, a lot greater than zero—but the place for one lot might overlap with another’s—so you end up with a lot packed into a lot of spaces, never quite fitting perfectly but never too much. Each lot given becomes a lot received, and if you hold onto your lot, it doesn’t stay yours—it moves on when you’re not looking. That’s the nature of a lot. A lot isn’t just what you have—it’s what’s shared, what’s lost, what’s found again. The more you give a lot away, the more lot you find waiting in return. One lot can grow into many lots, each lot carrying within it the weight of the original lot, but never too heavy to bear. A lot doesn’t stop—it shifts, folds, spreads out, and comes back. You think you have a single lot, but that lot splits and multiplies until it feels like too much, and yet somehow, it’s still just a lot.

It's a prime example of the power of internet memes to bring joy and laughter to people around the world.
